      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm studying regularization for my ml class and im a bit stuck. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization in terms of how they actually affect the model coefficients? like why would i pick one over the other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! L1 and L2 regularization are both methods to prevent overfitting in machine learning models, but they affect the model coefficients differently. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, tends to shrink some coefficients exactly to zero, effectively performing feature selection. This is because L1 adds the absolute value of the coefficients to the loss function, which encourages sparsity in the model. On the other hand, L2 regularization, known as Ridge, tends to shrink the coefficients towards zero but rarely exactly to zero. L2 adds the squared value of the coefficients to the loss function, which encourages smaller coefficients but doesn't necessarily eliminate any features. You might pick L1 over L2 if you believe some features are irrelevant and you want the model to automatically select a simpler model, while L2 might be a better choice if you believe all features are relevant but their coefficients should be small.",
